I'll create the following file: [38;5;141m/tmp/ralph-worktrees/iter-1245/chapter08.02-patient-sentiment-analysis.md[0m[38;5;244m (using tool: write)[0m

[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 8.2: Patient Sentiment Analysis
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Simple · **Phase:** MVP · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.01 per feedback item
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Every healthcare organization collects patient feedback. HCAHPS surveys, Press Ganey scores, post-visit satisfaction questionnaires, patient portal messages, online reviews, complaint hotline transcripts, social media mentions. The volume is enormous and growing. A mid-sized health system might receive 50,000 pieces of written feedback per month across all channels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's the problem: almost nobody reads it all.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most organizations track the quantitative scores (your "4.2 out of 5" star rating) and call it done. Maybe someone in Patient Experience reads a sample of the verbatim comments. But the text, the actual words patients use to describe their experience, contains information that a number never can. A patient who writes "the nurse was kind but I waited two hours and nobody told me why" is telling you three distinct things: a positive staff interaction, a process failure, and a communication gap. A "3 out of 5" rating flattens all of that into noise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Sentiment analysis turns that unstructured text into structured signal. Not just "positive or negative" (though that's a start), but which aspects of the experience are driving dissatisfaction, which departments are generating complaints, what themes emerge over time, and where the bright spots are hiding. Done well, it's an early warning system for operational issues and a map of what your patients actually care about.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The stakes are real. CMS ties a portion of hospital reimbursement to patient experience scores through the Hospital Value-Based Purchasing Program. Press Ganey and HCAHPS scores directly affect revenue. And beyond the financial incentive: patients who feel unheard leave. They switch providers, they post negative reviews, they tell their friends. Understanding sentiment at scale is understanding your retention risk.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's talk about how the technology works.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: How Machines Understand Feelings (Sort Of)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Sentiment Analysis: The Basics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Sentiment analysis is the task of automatically determining the emotional tone of a piece of text. At its simplest, it classifies text as positive, negative, or neutral. At its more useful, it identifies the intensity of sentiment, the specific aspects being discussed, and the emotions expressed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The field has been around since the early 2000s. Early approaches used hand-crafted word lists: "good" is positive, "terrible" is negative, add up the scores. These lexicon-based methods are fast, interpretable, and surprisingly stubborn in their continued usefulness. But they miss context entirely. "Not bad" has a negative word but positive meaning. "The procedure was painless" has "painless" (negative root) but is expressing relief.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Modern approaches use machine learning. A model trained on thousands of labeled examples learns the relationship between word patterns and sentiment. The dominant architecture for the past few years has been transformer-based models (BERT and its variants), fine-tuned on domain-specific data. These models understand context, handle negation, and capture subtle sentiment signals that word lists miss entirely.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m (A quick note: LLMs like GPT-4 can absolutely do sentiment analysis, and often quite well. This recipe focuses on traditional NLP approaches because they're faster, cheaper, more predictable, and perfectly adequate for this use case. You don't need a rocket to deliver a pizza. Recipe 2.1 covers when LLMs make sense for text analysis.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Aspect-Based Sentiment: The Real Value
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Raw sentiment classification ("this review is negative") tells you almost nothing actionable. You already knew some patients are unhappy. What you need is aspect-based sentiment analysis (ABSA): identifying which specific aspect of the experience the patient is commenting on, and what their sentiment is toward that specific aspect.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Consider: "Dr. Martinez was wonderful but the billing department never answers the phone." That's positive sentiment toward `provider_quality` and negative sentiment toward `billing_communication`. Two distinct signals from one sentence. Aggregate those across 10,000 reviews and you can tell the CFO exactly which operational area is driving dissatisfaction, with evidence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The aspects you care about in healthcare are fairly consistent:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Wait time and scheduling
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Provider communication and bedside manner
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Staff friendliness and competence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Facility cleanliness and environment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Billing and insurance processes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Care coordination and follow-up
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Pain management
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Discharge process
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ABSA typically works in two stages: first, identify which aspect(s) are mentioned in the text; second, determine the sentiment directed at each one. Some systems do both jointly with a single model. Either way, you need training data that's labeled at the aspect level, which is more expensive to create than simple positive/negative labels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Theme Extraction: Discovering What You Didn't Know to Ask About
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Beyond predefined aspects, you want the system to surface emergent themes: patterns you didn't anticipate. Maybe there's a cluster of complaints about parking in February (construction project you forgot about). Maybe patients keep mentioning "the lady at the front desk with the red glasses" positively (a staff member creating exceptional experiences that nobody in leadership knows about).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Theme extraction uses topic modeling or clustering techniques to group semantically similar feedback without predefined categories. The classic approach is Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA), but newer methods using sentence embeddings and clustering (HDBSCAN, k-means on embeddings) produce more coherent topics and handle short text better.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The output is a set of discovered themes with representative examples. These need human review to name and validate, but they surface blind spots that a predefined aspect taxonomy will miss.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Makes Healthcare Sentiment Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Standard sentiment analysis tooling was built for product reviews and social media. Healthcare feedback has several properties that make it harder:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mixed sentiment is the norm, not the exception.** Product reviews tend to be uniformly positive or negative. Patient feedback is almost always a mix: "the surgery went well but recovery was awful." You need aspect-level analysis or you lose the signal entirely.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical language intersects with emotional language.** "The pain was excruciating" is describing a symptom, not necessarily expressing dissatisfaction with care. "Negative" in "the test came back negative" is good news. Domain-specific context matters enormously.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Indirectness and understatement.** Patients expressing serious dissatisfaction often hedge: "I'm sure the staff was doing their best, but..." or "I don't want to complain, however..." Lexicon-based systems will score these as positive or neutral because of the hedging language. A healthcare-tuned model needs to recognize that politeness patterns often mask the strongest negative sentiment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and demographic variation.** Sentiment expression varies significantly across age groups, cultural backgrounds, and education levels. Older patients tend to rate everything higher (acquiescence bias). Patients from cultures where direct criticism is impolite will express dissatisfaction through absence of praise rather than explicit negativity. Your model needs to handle this gracefully or you'll systematically undercount dissatisfaction in certain populations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **PHI contamination.** Patient feedback frequently contains protected health information: names of providers, specific diagnoses, dates of service, medication names. Any system processing this text must handle PHI appropriately. The sentiment analysis itself doesn't need the PHI (you're extracting themes, not re-identifying patients), but the pipeline must protect it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Conceptually, the pipeline looks like this:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Collect] → [Preprocess] → [Analyze Sentiment] → [Extract Aspects/Themes] → [Aggregate] → [Visualize/Alert]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Collect.** Feedback arrives from multiple channels: survey platforms, patient portals, call transcripts, social media, email. Each has a different format, different metadata, and different response characteristics. You need a unified ingestion layer that normalizes these into a common schema.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Preprocess.** Clean the text: handle encoding issues, strip HTML, normalize whitespace. For healthcare, add a PHI detection pass: identify and redact or tag any protected information before it flows to downstream analytics. Also detect the language (multilingual patient populations are real) and decide whether to translate or route to a language-specific model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Analyze Sentiment.** Run the cleaned text through your sentiment model. For production use, you want both document-level sentiment (overall tone) and sentence-level sentiment (where in the text does sentiment shift?). Capture confidence scores. Low-confidence predictions should be flagged for review rather than treated as truth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Extract Aspects/Themes.** Identify which aspects of the experience are mentioned and attach sentiment to each. Separately, run topic modeling or clustering to discover emergent themes that your predefined aspects don't cover.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Aggregate.** Roll up results by time period, department, provider, facility, service line, and demographic segment. Calculate trend lines. Detect statistically significant shifts (a department's sentiment dropping 15% in two weeks is signal; a 2% fluctuation is noise).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Visualize/Alert.** Surface insights through dashboards for patient experience teams. Configure alerts for significant negative trends. Generate periodic reports for department leaders. The output should be actionable, not just informational.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend for sentiment and entity detection.** Comprehend is AWS's managed NLP service. Its sentiment analysis API classifies text as positive, negative, neutral, or mixed, with confidence scores for each. Crucially for healthcare, it also has a medical variant (Comprehend Medical) that detects PHI entities, which you need for the preprocessing step. You don't need to train, host, or scale any models. The tradeoff: Comprehend's built-in sentiment is document-level and uses generic categories. For aspect-level analysis, you'll need the custom classification feature or a separate model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend Custom Classification for aspect detection.** Comprehend lets you train custom classifiers on your labeled data. Train one model on your aspect taxonomy (wait_time, provider_communication, billing, etc.) and a second for fine-grained sentiment if the built-in model doesn't capture healthcare-specific nuance well enough. Custom models run on the same managed infrastructure, so you still don't manage servers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for feedback storage.** All incoming feedback lands in S3 as the durable data lake. Organized by source, date, and processing stage. S3 event notifications trigger the analysis pipeline automatically as new feedback arrives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** Each step in the pipeline (PHI detection, sentiment analysis, aspect extraction, result storage) is a short-lived, stateless function. Lambda handles the glue logic: calling Comprehend APIs, parsing responses, routing results. For batch processing of historical feedback, Step Functions coordinates the workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for results.** Analyzed results (sentiment scores, aspects, themes, metadata) are stored in DynamoDB for fast lookup by survey ID, date range, or department. The table design supports the access patterns dashboards need: "show me all negative-sentiment feedback for cardiology in the last 30 days."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon QuickSight for visualization.** QuickSight connects to DynamoDB (via Athena or direct) to power patient experience dashboards. Trend charts, department comparisons, theme word clouds, and drill-down to individual comments. The patient experience team lives in these dashboards.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for alerting.** When aggregation detects a significant negative trend (configurable thresholds), EventBridge routes an alert to the appropriate team via SNS, Slack, or PagerDuty. Early warning, not just retrospective reporting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart LR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[📋 Survey Platform\nPatient Portal\nCall Transcripts] -->|Ingest| B[S3 Bucket\nfeedback-raw/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|S3 Event| C[Lambda\nphi-detection]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Comprehend Medical\nDetectPHI| D[S3\nfeedback-redacted/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|S3 Event| E[Lambda\nsentiment-analyzer]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Comprehend\nDetectSentiment| F[Lambda\naspect-extractor]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Custom Classifier| G[DynamoDB\nsentiment-results]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Query| H[QuickSight\nDashboards]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Trend Detection| I[EventBridge\nAlerts]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style D fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style G fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style H fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend, Comprehend Medical, S3, Lambda, DynamoDB, QuickSight, EventBridge, SNS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend:DetectSentiment`, `comprehend:ClassifyDocument`, `comprehend:DetectPiiEntities`, `comprehendmedical:DetectPHI`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | Required: patient feedback often contains PHI (names, dates, diagnoses mentioned in free text) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); Lambda logs: KMS-encrypted CloudWatch log groups; all API calls over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, Comprehend, DynamoDB, and CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all Comprehend and S3 API calls for audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic patient feedback. CMS publishes [HCAHPS survey results](https://data.cms.gov/provider-data/topics/hospitals/overall-hospital-quality-star-rating) (aggregate only). Generate synthetic verbatim comments for development. Never use real patient feedback in non-production environments without proper de-identification. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend DetectSentiment: $0.0001 per unit (100 chars). For average 500-char feedback: ~$0.0005/item. PHI detection adds ~$0.01/item. Custom classification: $0.0005/item. At 50,000 items/month: ~$550/month total. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend** | Sentiment detection (built-in) and custom aspect classification |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | PHI entity detection for preprocessing/redaction |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Raw and redacted feedback storage; organized by source and date |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestration: PHI detection, sentiment analysis, aspect extraction, result assembly |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores analyzed results for dashboard queries and trend detection |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Patient experience dashboards and visualizations |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Routes trend alerts to appropriate teams |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing resources |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Metrics, logs, and alarms for pipeline health |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-comprehend-examples`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-comprehend-examples): General Comprehend examples including sentiment analysis, custom classification, and entity detection
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-comprehend-medical-fhir-integration`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-comprehend-medical-fhir-integration): Healthcare-specific: integrating Comprehend Medical with FHIR for clinical NLP pipelines
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: PHI detection and redaction.** Before any analysis, the system scans incoming feedback for protected health information. Patient comments routinely mention provider names, specific diagnoses, medication names, and dates of service. The PHI detection pass identifies these entities and either redacts them (replaces with placeholder tokens like `[PROVIDER_NAME]`) or tags them for downstream handling. This step is non-negotiable for any pipeline processing patient-generated text. The redacted version is what flows to sentiment analysis, so your sentiment models never need access to identifiable information. Skip this step and you're running PHI through analytics services without proper safeguards.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION detect_and_redact_phi(feedback_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Call the medical NLP service to identify any PHI in the text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // PHI includes: names, dates, phone numbers, medical record numbers,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // and any other individually identifiable health information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     phi_entities = call ComprehendMedical.DetectPHI with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         text = feedback_text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Build the redacted version by replacing each detected entity with a placeholder.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // We preserve the entity type so downstream analysis knows a provider was mentioned
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // even though we've removed the actual name.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     redacted_text = feedback_text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each entity in phi_entities (sorted by offset, descending):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Replace from back to front so character offsets remain valid.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Example: "Dr. Smith was kind" becomes "[PROVIDER_NAME] was kind"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         redacted_text = replace characters at entity.BeginOffset..entity.EndOffset
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         with "[" + entity.Type + "]"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         redacted_text:  redacted_text,      // safe for downstream analytics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phi_detected:   length(phi_entities) > 0,  // flag for audit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         entity_count:   length(phi_entities)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Sentiment analysis.** The redacted text goes to the sentiment analysis service. This returns an overall sentiment label (POSITIVE, NEGATIVE, NEUTRAL, MIXED) along with confidence scores for each category. The confidence distribution is often more informative than the top label. A comment scored 60% negative and 35% positive is qualitatively different from one scored 95% negative. The MIXED category is especially important in healthcare feedback, where patients commonly express both gratitude and frustration in the same response. Store the full score distribution, not just the winning label.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION analyze_sentiment(redacted_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Call the sentiment detection service.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Input must be under 5,000 bytes (UTF-8). Patient feedback typically fits easily.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For longer texts (call transcripts), split into paragraphs and analyze each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = call Comprehend.DetectSentiment with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         text          = redacted_text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         language_code = "en"    // detect language first for multilingual populations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Extract the full score distribution, not just the top label.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // A 55% negative / 40% positive split tells a different story than 95% negative.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sentiment:    response.Sentiment,           // "POSITIVE", "NEGATIVE", "NEUTRAL", "MIXED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         scores: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             positive: response.SentimentScore.Positive,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             negative: response.SentimentScore.Negative,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             neutral:  response.SentimentScore.Neutral,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             mixed:    response.SentimentScore.Mixed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         confidence:   maximum of all four scores    // how decisive the classification is
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Aspect extraction.** This is where generic sentiment becomes actionable intelligence. The system classifies which aspect(s) of the healthcare experience are mentioned in each piece of feedback. A custom classifier trained on your labeled data maps text segments to your aspect taxonomy. For each detected aspect, the system also captures the sentiment directed specifically at that aspect. One comment might yield: `{wait_time: NEGATIVE, provider_quality: POSITIVE, facility: NEUTRAL}`. That's three distinct operational signals from one piece of text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // The aspect taxonomy reflects what patient experience teams actually care about.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // This should be configured, not hardcoded. Add/remove aspects as your organization evolves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ASPECT_TAXONOMY = [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "wait_time",              // scheduling delays, in-office wait
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "provider_communication", // bedside manner, explanations, listening
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "staff_interaction",      // nursing, front desk, technicians
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "facility_environment",   // cleanliness, comfort, noise, parking
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "billing_insurance",      // charges, statements, coverage confusion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "care_coordination",      // referrals, follow-up, transitions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "pain_management",        // pain control, medication responsiveness
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "discharge_process",      // instructions, timing, readiness
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "access_convenience",     // hours, location, telehealth availability
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "overall_experience"      // general impressions not tied to specific aspect
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_aspects(redacted_text, document_sentiment):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Split text into sentences for finer-grained analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // A single feedback item often covers multiple aspects across sentences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sentences = split_into_sentences(redacted_text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     aspect_results = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each sentence in sentences:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Classify which aspect this sentence is about.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Uses a custom classifier trained on labeled healthcare feedback.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         aspect_response = call Comprehend.ClassifyDocument with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             text             = sentence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             endpoint_arn     = ASPECT_CLASSIFIER_ENDPOINT
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Get the top aspect prediction with confidence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         top_aspect     = aspect_response.Classes[0].Name
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         aspect_conf    = aspect_response.Classes[0].Score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Only accept aspect classification if confidence is above threshold.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Low-confidence aspect assignments add noise to dashboards.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF aspect_conf >= 0.6:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Get sentence-level sentiment for this specific aspect mention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             sentence_sentiment = call Comprehend.DetectSentiment with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text          = sentence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 language_code = "en"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to aspect_results: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 aspect:     top_aspect,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 sentiment:  sentence_sentiment.Sentiment,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence: aspect_conf,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text:       sentence   // keep the source text for drill-down
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN aspect_results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Result assembly and storage.** The final step combines all analysis outputs into a single record and writes it to the database. Each record links back to the source feedback item and includes the full analysis: document-level sentiment, aspect-level sentiments, metadata about the source channel and department, and processing timestamps. The table design supports the queries that dashboards need: filter by date range, department, sentiment, or aspect. The `needs_attention` flag routes significantly negative items to immediate human review rather than waiting for monthly reports.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_analysis_result(source_metadata, sentiment, aspects):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Determine if this item needs immediate human attention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Threshold: overall negative sentiment with high confidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // or any critical aspect (safety, pain) with negative sentiment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     needs_attention = (
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sentiment.sentiment == "NEGATIVE" AND sentiment.confidence >= 0.85
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ) OR any aspect in aspects where (
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         aspect.aspect in ["pain_management", "care_coordination"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         AND aspect.sentiment == "NEGATIVE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write the complete analysis record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write record to database table "sentiment-results":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         feedback_id       = source_metadata.id                    // links to original feedback
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         source_channel    = source_metadata.channel               // "survey", "portal", "review", "call"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         department        = source_metadata.department            // for departmental filtering
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         facility          = source_metadata.facility              // for multi-site systems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analysis_date     = current UTC timestamp (ISO 8601)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         document_sentiment = sentiment                            // full score distribution
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         aspects           = aspects                               // list of aspect-sentiment pairs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         needs_attention   = needs_attention                       // routes to review queue
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         feedback_date     = source_metadata.submitted_date        // when patient submitted
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If needs_attention, also emit an event for real-time alerting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF needs_attention:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         emit event to EventBridge:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             source     = "patient-sentiment-pipeline"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             detail_type = "NegativeSentimentAlert"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             detail     = { feedback_id, department, facility, top_negative_aspect }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
